A prime example of superexponential behavior is found in our evolutionary model. Here, the bene confers a fitness advantage to infected individuals, and, in contrast to a standard positive mutation, the bene can also be transmitted across individuals within a generation. One example of such a bene would be antibiotic-resistance cassettes49, where bacteria acquire genes from neighboring cells that increase survival when exposed to antibiotics. Our model shows that horizontal transfer of such elements, even when vertical transmission is imperfect, dramatically reduces the time required to fully infect the population. The superexponential decrease in the susceptible population occurs when \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
